RECURRING ISSUE - Port 4000 EADDRINUSE
================================================================================

Observed behavior:
- Repeated Error: listen EADDRINUSE: address already in use :::4000
- When trying to run npm start multiple times in different terminals

Root cause:
- npm run dev (nodemon) leaves the server running in background
- Running npm start in another terminal tries to use the same port
- Old process hasn't been killed yet

Prevention & Quick Fix:
When you see EADDRINUSE port 4000:

1. Kill all related processes:
   pkill -f "nodemon index.js"
   pkill -f "node index.js"

2. Verify port is free:
   lsof -nP -iTCP:4000 -sTCP:LISTEN
   (should return nothing)

3. Start one server:
   npm run dev    (for development with auto-restart)
   OR
   npm start      (for production, but only use ONE)

Best practice:
- Use ONLY npm run dev during development
- Do NOT use npm run dev AND npm start simultaneously
- Keep only one server instance running at a time

================================================================================
SUMMARY OF KEY FIXES & PATTERNS
================================================================================

1. MongoDB Atlas:
   - Always whitelist your IP in Network Access before connecting
   - Remove tls: true from mongoose.connect() (connection string handles TLS)

2. Module paths:
   - Use exact filenames: '../models/events' not '../models/event'
   - Check real filenames in the directory before requiring

3. Async/Await:
   - Always await database operations: await User.findById()
   - Always await mongoose methods: await event.populate(), await event.save()

4. Mongoose References:
   - Use .populate() to fetch related objects
   - Use .toObject() to convert Mongoose documents to plain JavaScript objects
   - Avoid ._doc as it loses populated references

5. GraphQL Schema & Data:
   - Make fields nullable if old/legacy data can have null values
   - Match schema nullability to actual data availability

6. Input Validation:
   - Always validate required inputs in resolvers
   - Throw UserInputError for empty/invalid parameters before database queries

7. Port Conflicts:
   - Check running processes: ps aux | grep node
   - Find port usage: lsof -nP -iTCP:PORT -sTCP:LISTEN
   - Kill cleanly: pkill -f "pattern" instead of kill PID

8. Development Workflow:
   - npm run dev for development (includes auto-restart with nodemon)
   - npm start for production (plain node)
   - Keep only one instance running
   - Use git to track code changes, not manual process management

